# Using Dynatrace OpenPipeline by Grail for processing rules and metric extraction  
#
### Overview
___
#
Duration: 10 min
#
### Use Case
* Understand, how to use OpenPipeline to process, route, create metrics and enrich data ingested to Grail.
#
### What Youâ€™ll Learn Today 
#
1. Simulate ingest of data in the tenant using workflows and javascript.
2. Create DPL to extract important data to fields.
3. Create Pipeline with the DPL, use the log ingested via workflows to verify.
4. Create metric based on the DPL.
5. Create a Dynamic routing associated with the pipeline created.
6. Verify pipeline created and metric extraction is working.

#
Dynatrace Log Management and Analytics, powered by Grail, provides a unified approach to unlocking the value of log data in the Dynatrace platform. Hassle-free management of your log data lets you store petabytes of data without schemas, indexing, or rehydration. All of that data is usable at any time for any analytics task. Thanks to schema on-read and the Dynatrace Query Language, there's no need to decide what you want to query during data ingestion. Pick the retention period for your data that fits your business and compliance needs, whether debugging or audit.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
OpenPipeline is the Dynatrace data handling solution to seamlessly ingest and process data from different sources, at any scale, and in any format in the Dynatrace Platform.

### Use cases
* Configure ingestion and processing of different data types, such as logs and events, via a unified solution.
* Scala data management across teams by controlling access and targeted technologies.
* Ensure secure and compliant sensitive data handling.
* Enrich and contextualize data via customizable data processing.
* Optimize data quality and cost control.
#
With OpenPipeline, you can ingest data in the Dynatrace platform from a wide variety of formats and providers, through ingest sources. Data is then routed to pipelines for processing, and stored in Grail buckets.
#
![](https://dt-cdn.net/images/openpipeline-2500-87f73d19d1.png)


 Reference: [OpenPipeline](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/openpipeline-dataflow)

## Step 1: Permissions/Policies

### Create 2 Policies

#### Log Ingest Policy (for workflow)
```
ALLOW storage:logs:write;
```

![](data:image/webp;base64,)

#### OpenPipeline Policy (For OpenPipeline App)
```
ALLOW openpipeline:configurations:read, openpipeline:configurations:write;
```

![](data:image/webp;base64,)

## Step 2: Group and Policy Assignment

### Create Group
```
Name: OpenPipeline 
```

### Assign policies to the OpenPipeline Group
```
Log Ingest

OpenPipeline
```

## Step 3: Assign Group to User
#### Assign Group (OpenPipeline) to your user id.

## Step 4: Simulate ingest of data in the tenant using workflows and javascript
#
To simulate over time the ingest of log samples to the tenant we are going to use workflows with 2 steps, the trigger is going to be a time interval every 3,5 and 7 minutes.

Look at the following example for reference of the workflow:

![](data:image/webp;base64,)

Here the template of the workflow you can use and change randomly the productID and price in the content of the log lines, if you want to use it, copy the code and save as a .yaml, or copy the workflow from the following [link](https://bwm98081.apps.dynatrace.com/ui/apps/dynatrace.automations/workflows/3dc315c9-77e1-4a6f-b7b5-00172a28aebc):

```
metadata:
  version: "1"
  dependencies:
    apps:
      - id: dynatrace.automations
        version: ^1.814.0
  inputs: []
workflow:
  title: OpenPipeline
  tasks:
    run_javascript_1:
      name: run_javascript_1
      description: Build a custom task running js Code
      action: dynatrace.automations:run-javascript
      input:
        script: >-
          import { logsClient } from
          '@dynatrace-sdk/client-classic-environment-v2';


          const logs = [
            {
              'content': 'The price of the product 273EIR is $56',
              'log.source': '/var/open/syslog',
              'log.tag': ['tag1', 'pipe'],
            },
            {
              'content': 'The price of the product 938RNG is $49',
              'log.source': '/var/open/syslog',
              'log.tag': ['tag1', 'pipe'],
            },
          ];


          logsClient
            .storeLog({
              body: logs,
              type: 'application/json; charset=utf-8',
            })
            .then((response) => console.log(response))
            .catch((e) => console.error(e));
      position:
        x: 0
        y: 1
      predecessors: []
    run_javascript_2:
      name: run_javascript_2
      description: Build a custom task running js Code
      action: dynatrace.automations:run-javascript
      input:
        script: >-
          import { logsClient } from
          '@dynatrace-sdk/client-classic-environment-v2';


          const logs = [
            {
              'content': 'The price of the product 285VJS is $27',
              'log.source': '/var/open/syslog',
              'log.tag': ['tag1', 'pipe'],
            },
            {
              'content': 'The price of the product 386SLB is $37',
              'log.source': '/var/open/syslog',
              'log.tag': ['tag1', 'pipe'],
            },
          ];


          logsClient
            .storeLog({
              body: logs,
              type: 'application/json; charset=utf-8',
            })
            .then((response) => console.log(response))
            .catch((e) => console.error(e));
      position:
        x: -1
        y: 1
      predecessors: []
  description: ""
  trigger:
    schedule:
      rule: null
      trigger:
        type: interval
        intervalMinutes: 1
      timezone: America/Mexico_City
      isActive: false
      isFaulty: false
      filterParameters:
        earliestStart: 2024-07-17
        earliestStartTime: 00:00
      inputs: {}
  schemaVersion: 3


```
#
TIP: you can ingest logs and bizevents using javascript, here the doc from dynatrace developer: [Ingest via javascript](https://developer.dynatrace.com/develop/data/ingest-data/#logs)

## Step 8: Create a new pipeline
### Processing
```
Pipeline Name: Bootcamp-LogPipeline
Processor Name: ProcessLogData
Processor Type: DQL
Matching Condition: matchesPhrase(content,"The price of the product")
DQL processor definition: parse content, """'The price of the product ' LD:product' is $' DOUBLE:price"""
Sample Data:
{
      "timestamp": "2024-08-26T13:07:02.319000000-07:00",
      "content": "The price of the product 285VJS is $27",
      "log.source": "/var/open/syslog",
      "loglevel": "NONE",
      "status": "NONE",
      "dt.openpipeline.pipelines": [
        "logs:pipeline_ParseProductLog_3301"
      ],
      "log.tag": [
        "tag1",
        "pipe"
      ],
      "price": 27,
      "product": "285VJS"
}
```

![](data:image/webp;base64,)
### Metric Extraction
```
Processor: Value Metric
Name: Extract Pricing
Matching condition: matchesPhrase(content,"The price of the product")
Field Extraction: price
Metric Key: log.open.price
Dimensions: Custom
Dimension Value: product
```

![](data:image/webp;base64,)
### Data Extraction
```
Processor: Business Event
Name: BizEventFromLog
Matching condition: matchesPhrase(content,"The price of the product")
Event Type: Static String
Event Type Value: log.open.price
Event Provider: Static String
Event Provider Value: log.open
Field Extraction: Extract all fields
```
![](data:image/webp;base64,)

## Step 9: Create Dynamic Route
```
Name: ProductPriceRoute
Matching Condition: matchesPhrase(content,"The price of the product")
Pipeline: Bootcamp-LogPipeline
```
![](data:image/webp;base64,)

## Step 10: Verify pipeline created and metric extraction is working
#
To verify the Pipeline, you can go to the notebook and execute the following DQL, here you are going to find the log parsed by the procesing rule of the pipeline or you can search for the `dt.openpipeline.pipelines` fields where your are going to find the associated pipeline.
Also,you can search for the metric key ``log.open.price`` in the below "Explore Metrics" section
